body.text:
Note you can't buy tickets through the Eventbrite iPhone app. Please use a web browser.

Do you feel stressed and tired all the time? Do you feel like you have nothing left to give? How do you look after yourself when everyone else needs looking after?

If you are feeling burnt out caring for your children and family, this new webinar will give you plenty of ideas and practical exercises to help!

Abigail will use evidence based exercises, imagery and polyvagal theory to give you a better understanding of how your nervous system works and how you can harness this to help you feel better, even as the demands on you feel overwhelming.

It is a practical session to help you relax, reduce stress levels and improve your overall wellbeing.

Dr Abigail Fisher is an educational psychologist and qualified teacher. She has a particular interest in supporting parents to look after themselves so they can better care for their families. She uses imagery and guided exercises to help parents find space for themsleves in amongst family life.

Feedback from previous webinars:

I have appreciated this session so much. In the midst of a very difficult time I really needed this.

I felt very connected and this felt like a very personal session. It was very nurturing.

faqs.answer: There is a problem with the Eventbrite iPhone app. If you use a web browser such as Chrome or Safari you should be able to buy tickets.
faqs.question: Why can't I buy tickets for this event?

faqs.answer: Eventbrite will send out a reminder 2 hours before the event and 10 minutes before the event you will be emailed the Zoom details
faqs.question: When do I get sent the Zoom link for the event?

faqs.answer: Yes, if you choose the webinar + recording option you can watch it in your own time
faqs.question: Can I miss the webinar and watch it later?

faqs.answer: We'll send a link by the morning after the webinar
faqs.question: When do I get sent a link to the recording?

faqs.answer: You can watch the recording for at least 2 weeks after the webinar
faqs.question: How long can I watch the recording for?
